  "prompt": "What will happen to the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland following the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "Following the Brexit vote, the border between Northern Ireland (part of the United Kingdom) and the Republic of Ireland (an EU member) became a significant issue. The primary concern was to avoid the establishment of a hard border, which could undermine the Good Friday Agreement that helped to bring peace to Northern Ireland after decades of conflict.\n\nThe solution reached was the Northern Ireland Protocol, part of the Withdrawal Agreement between the UK and the EU. Key points of the Protocol include:\n\n1. **No Hard Border**: There would be no physical infrastructure or checks at the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.\n\n2. **Customs and Regulatory Checks**: While Northern Ireland remains part of the UK customs territory, it follows some EU rules to prevent goods from the EU entering the UK without checks. This means that some checks and controls are required on goods moving from Great Britain to Northern Ireland.\n\n3. **Political and Social Concerns**: The arrangement has led to ongoing political tensions, particularly among unionist communities in Northern Ireland who feel it creates a de facto border in the Irish Sea, separating Northern Ireland from the rest of the UK.\n\nAs of my last knowledge update in October 2023, discussions and negotiations regarding the protocol and its implementation were ongoing, with various proposals and adjustments being considered in response to political dynamics and public sentiment in Northern Ireland.",
